    <subsection>
        <title>Domain of the Log Function</title>
        <p>Here is a graph of <m>y=\log_2(x)</m>. Zoom in and out some, and move the graph up, down, left, and right. This is all to explore the graph and give you a fell for it.</p>
        <todo>Insert GeoGebra here. Possibly rework with the above line into a captioned figure or something.</todo>
        <p>Try to evaluate <m>\log(-100)</m> on your calculator. What value does your caluclator return? Your calculator should read <q>error</q> or <q>quit</q> or something indicating it cannot be done. To understand why this is true, write out the meaning of <m>\log(-100)</m> in English.</p>
        <exercise>
            <webwork seed="1">
                <setup>
                    <var name="$c">
                        <static>-100</static>
                    </var>
                    <var name="$b">
                        <static>10</static>
                    </var>
                    <pg-code>
                        $b=10;
                        $c=-$b**random(-2,4,1);
                        if($envir{problemSeed}==1){$c=-100;};
                    </pg-code>
                </setup>
                <statement>
                    <p>Translate the math expression below into what it would mean in English (even if the statement ultimately makes no sense).</p>
                    <p><m>\log(<var name="$c" />)</m></p>
                    <p>The power of <var name="$b" width="1"/> that gives you <var name="$c" width="2"/>.</p>
                </statement>
            </webwork>
        </exercise>

        <p>If you have a bunch of positive <m>10</m>s then how many do you have to multiply to get a <em>negative</em> <m>100</m>? In fact, you <em>can't</em> get a negative result if you only have positive <m>10</m>s! You would need at least one negative <m>10</m> and you don't have any.</p>

        <p>Try to evaluate <m>\log(0)</m> on your calculator. What value does your caluclator return? Your calculator should read <q>error</q> or <q>quit</q> or something indicating it cannot be done. To understand why this is true, write out the meaning of <m>\log(0)</m> in English.</p>
        <exercise>
