    <subsection>
        <title>Properties of Logarithms (how we use logs to solve equations)</title>

        <p>In order for this part of the activity to make sense, you have to remember what a <term>base</term> and an <term>expoenent</term> is. Remember that in the expression <m>b^x</m>, that <m>b</m> is the <term>base</term> and <m>x</m> is the exponent. The exponent literally counts how many times you multiplied the base. For instance <m>b^7</m> means <m>\overbrace{b\cdot b\cdot b\cdot b\cdot b\cdot b\cdot b}^{7\text{ times}}</m>.</p>

        <subsubsection>
            <title>Big Rule About Logs <hash />1</title>

            <p>We start with a very simple rule for exponents: <m>x^a\cdot x^b=x^{a+b}</m>. When you multiply numbers of the same base you add the exponents.</p>

            <exercise>
                <webwork seed="1">
                    <pg-macros>
                        <macro-file>bizarroArithmetic.pl</macro-file>
                    </pg-macros>
                    <setup>
                        <var name="$b">
                            <static>2</static>
                        </var>
                        <var name="$x">
                            <static>3</static>
                        </var>
                        <var name="$y">
                            <static>4</static>
                        </var>
                        <var name="$z">
                            <static>7</static>
                        </var>
                        <var name="$bx">
                            <static>8</static>
                        </var>
                        <var name="$by">
                            <static>16</static>
                        </var>
                        <var name="$bz">
                            <static>128</static>
                        </var>
                        <var name="$N">
                            <static>2^7</static>
                        </var>
                        <pg-code>
                            Context()->operators->set(
                                '**' => {class => 'bizarro::BOP::power', isCommand => 1, perl=>undef},
                                '^' => {class => 'bizarro::BOP::power', isCommand => 1, perl=>undef},
                            );
                            $b = random(2,5,1);
                            $x = random(2,5,1);
                            do{$y=random(2,5,1)} until($x!=$y);
                            if($envir{problemSeed}==1){$b=2;$x=3;$y=4;};
                            $z=$x+$y;
                            Context()->flags->set(reduceConstants=>0);
                            $N=Formula("$b^$z");
                            $evaluator=$N->cmp(checker=>sub{
                                my($c,$s,$aH)=@_;
                                return 0 if $aH->{isPreview}||$c!=$s;
                                $s=$aH->{student_formula};
                                $c=$c->{original_formula} if defined $c->{original_formula};
                                $s= Formula("$s");$c=Formula("$c");
                                return 0 unless ($c==$s);
                                Context()->flags->set(bizarroPow=>1);
                                delete $c->{test_values}, $s->{test_values};
                                my $OK = (($c==$s) or ($s==$c));
                                Context()->flags->set(bizarroPow=>0);
                                Value::Error("This is the right number, but right now you are being asked to write it in a certain exponential form.") unless $OK;
                                return $OK;
                            }); 
                            Context("LimitedNumeric");
                            $bx=Real($b**$x);
                            $by=Real($b**$y);
                            $bz=Real($b**$z);
                        </pg-code>
                    </setup>
                    <statement>
                        <p>What is <m>N</m> if <m>N=<var name="$b" />^<var name="$x" />\cdot <var name="$b" />^<var name="$y" /></m>?</p>
                        <p><m>N=</m><var name="$N" evaluator="$evaluator" width="10" />.</p>
                        <p>Check that this is valid by using a calculator to find:</p>
                        <p><m><var name="$b" />^<var name="$x" />=</m><var name="$bx" width="10" /></p>
                        <p><m><var name="$b" />^<var name="$y" />=</m><var name="$by" width="10" /></p>
                        <p><m><var name="$b" />^<var name="$z" />=</m><var name="$bz" width="10" /></p>
                        <p>and checking that the first two multiply to the third.</p> 
                        
                    </statement>
                </webwork>
            </exercise>
            <p>Now let's take some obvious information that you already concluded above to discover a not-so-obvious property of logarithms.</p>

            <p>Start with the simple equation <me>8\cdot16=128\text{.}</me>Apply the <m>\log_2(\phantom{x})</m> funciton to both sides of the equation to get <me>\log_2(8\cdot16)=\log_2(128)\text{.}</me> Notice on the right side we already know the answer.</p>
            <exercise>
                <webwork seed="1">
                    <setup>
                        <var name="$seven">
                            <static>7</static>
                        </var>
                        <pg-code>
                            $seven=7;
                        </pg-code>
                    </setup>
                    <statement>
                        <p>What power of <m>2</m> gives you <m>128</m>?</p>
                        <p><var name="$seven" width="15" /></p>
                    </statement>
                </webwork>
            </exercise>

            <p>Now you can write the equation as <me>\log_2(8\cdot16)=7\text{.}</me></p>

            <p>Check this out on the left side of the equation:<ul>
                <li>There are <m>3</m> factors of <m>2</m> in <m>8</m>. That's why <m>\log_2(8)=3</m>.</li>
                <li>There are <m>4</m> factors of <m>2</m> in <m>16</m>. That's why <m>\log_2(8)=4</m>.</li>
            </ul>Since <m>3+4=7</m>, then we know that <me>\log_2(8)+\log_2(16)=7\text{.}</me></p>

            <p><em>What???</em></p>

            <p>Yes, you just discovered that <me>\log_2(8\cdot16)=\log_2(8)+\log_2(16)\text{.}</me> In fact it does not matter what the base is.</p>

            <exercise>
                <webwork seed="1">
                    <setup>
                        <var name="$log128">
                            <static>2.107</static>
                        </var>
                        <pg-code>
                            $log128=ln(128)/ln(10);
                            Context("LimitedNumeric");
                            $log128=Real($log128);
                        </pg-code>
                    </setup>
                    <statement>
                        <p>Use your calculator to find log base <m>10</m> of <m>128</m>:</p>
                        <p><m>\log(128)=</m><var name="$log128" width="15" /></p>
                        <p>Since <m>128=8\cdot16</m>, you can also use your calculator to find <m>\log(8)+\log(16)</m>:</p>
                        <p><m>\log(8)+\log(16)=</m><var name="$log128" width="15" /></p>
                    </statement>
                </webwork>
            </exercise>

            <p>In general, <em>for any base</em>, <me>\log_b(A\cdot B)=\log_b(A)+\log_b(B)\text{.}</me> Remember this rule! Put it on a note card for your next exam.</p>

        </subsubsection>

        <subsubsection>
            <title>Big Rule About Logs <hash />2</title>
            <p>Again, let's start with something obvious. You already know that instead of writing <m>8+8+8+8</m> you could just write <m>4\cdot8</m>. Maybe you never thought about it, but multiplication is just repeated addition. It's a shortcut way to write the same thing over and over. On the other hand, exponents are just repeated multiplication. Exponents are a shortcut way to write the same thing <em>multiplied</em> over and over.</p>

            <p>Consider the expression <m>\log(8\cdot8\cdot8\cdot8)</m>. We can use some shortcuts to write the expression in at least two different ways.<me>\log(8\cdot8\cdot8\cdot8)=\log\mathopen{}\left(8^4\right)\mathclose{}</me> and <me>\log(8\cdot8\cdot8\cdot8)=\log(8)+\log(8)+\log(8)+\log(8)\text{.}</me> This last equation is using Big Rule <hash />1.</p>

            <exercise>
                <webwork>
                    <pg-macros>
                        <macro-file>contextLimitedRadical.pl</macro-file>
                    </pg-macros>
                    <setup>
                        <var name="$answer">
                            <static>4\log(8)</static>
                        </var>
                        <pg-code>
                            Context("LimitedRadical");
                            $answer=Formula("4*log(8)");
                        </pg-code>
                    </setup>
                    <statement>
                        <p>Instead of writing the same term added over and over, rewrite <m>\log(8)+\log(8)+\log(8)+\log(8)</m> using multiplication:</p>
                        <p><m>\log(8)+\log(8)+\log(8)+\log(8)=</m><var name="$answer" width="10" /></p>
                    </statement>
                </webwork>
            </exercise>

            <p>So here is the big finale:</p>

            <exercise>
                <webwork>
                    <setup>
                        <var name="$c">
                            <static>4</static>
                        </var>
                        <var name="$N">
                            <static>N</static>
                        </var>
                        <pg-code>
                            $c=4;
                            Context()->variables->add(N=>'Real');
                            $N=Formula("N");
                        </pg-code>
                    </setup>
                    <statement>
                        <p><m>\log(8^4)=</m><var name="$c" width="2" /><m>{}\cdot\log(8)</m></p>
                        <p><m>\log(x^N)=</m><var name="$N" width="2" /><m>{}\cdot\log(x)</m></p>
                    </statement>
                </webwork>
            </exercise>

